{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521461"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:34:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13644"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13644"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.01,0.01,0.72,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6254"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112696"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6254"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13644"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94729"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"1545"},{"type":"tags","id":"5630"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12474"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39892"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46304"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112696"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old man collapses in a shopping centre. Bystanders report that he was complaining of chest pain, then sat down on the floor before he rolled over and collapsed. On arrival, you find him lying on the ground, unresponsive, not breathing normally, and without a pulse. You call for help and prepare to start cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial action to open the airway?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Jaw thrust","Oral airway insertion","Nasopharyngeal airway insertion","Head-tilt chin-lift","Neck extension"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehead-tilt chin-lift\u003C/strong\u003E technique is the most appropriate initial action to open the airway in an unconscious patient during cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR). This technique is simple and effective for relieving airway obstruction caused by the tongue in an unconscious patient. It involves tilting the head back and lifting the chin up, which moves the tongue away from the back of the throat.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ejaw thrust\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative method to open the airway, especially useful in patients where a spinal injury is suspected. However, it is more complex to perform correctly and is not the first choice in a sudden collapse without suspicion of spinal injury. It is unlikely that this patient has a spinal injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Enasopharyngeal airway\u003C/strong\u003E insertions are adjuncts to maintain an open airway and are used after initial airway opening maneuvers have been performed. They require specific training to insert correctly and safely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeck extension\u003C/strong\u003E alone is not recommended as a method to open the airway as it does not effectively lift the tongue away from the back of the throat and can potentially worsen any existing spinal injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Head-tilt chin-lift is a technique used in cardiopulmonary resuscitation (CPR) to open the airway of an unconscious patient."],"references":["Perkins GD, Handley AJ, Koster RW, Castr\u00e9n M, Smyth MA, Olasveengen T, Monsieurs KG, Raffay V, Gr\u00e4sner JT, Wenzel V, Ristagno G, Soar J. European Resuscitation Council Guidelines for Resuscitation 2015: Section 2. Adult basic life support and automated external defibrillation. Resuscitation. 2015 Oct;95:81-99. doi: 10.1016/j.resuscitation.2015.07.015. Epub 2015 Oct 15.","Kleinman ME, Brennan EE, Goldberger ZD, Swor RA, Terry M, Bobrow BJ, Gazmuri RJ, Travers AH, Rea T. Part 5: Adult Basic Life Support and Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation Quality: 2015 American Heart Association Guidelines Update for Cardiopulmonary Resuscitation and Emergency Cardiovascular Care. Circulation. 2015 Nov 3;132(18 Suppl 2):S414-35. doi: 10.1161/CIR.0000000000000259."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94729"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13644"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94729"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-03T20:34:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-03T20:36:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6254"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112696"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71"